Pre-heat the #oven{} to 220 degrees. Wash the @potato{4} then chop length-ways
into wedges the thickness of your index finger. Toss in @olive oil{1%tbsp} and
the @garlic salt{2%tsp}, then spread in a single layer on a #baking tray{}. Cook
on the top shelf of the oven until crispy (~{25%minutes}).

In a #bowl{} mix together the @minced beef{500%g} with a few grinds of
@pepper{some grinds}, a small pinch of @salt{pinch} and the @Stokes BBQ sauce{2%tbsp}.

Divide the mixture into 4 equal portions and then gently form into burger patties.
It is important that you press the meat together firmly enough to make it stick
yet not so firmly that it becomes densely packed, as this will give a tough texture.

Once the potatoes are almost finished, split the @brioche bun{4} in half. Put a
#frying pan{} on a #hob{} on medium-high heat. Toast the buns for a couple of
~{2%minutes} on each side then remove.

> You could use your toaster but whatever happens don't let them burn!

Heat @olive oil{1/2%tbsp} in a #non-stick pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot,
gently add in the patties and cook for ~{3-4%minutes} on each side, turning only
once.

> We love dribble-down-your-chin medium/rare which takes around 3 mins on each
> side but cook them for a little longer if you like.

Whilst you are cooking the second side of the burger slice the @mature cheddar
cheese{3}(sliced thinly) into thin slices and lay a couple of slices of cheese
on top of each. Put @water{2%tbsp} in the pan and put a #lid{} on for
~{1%minute}. Lift the lid off and the steam will have melted the cheese.

Toss the @wild rocket{1} in a drizzle of @olive oil{} and a small pinch of
@salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}.

Spread a little of the @ketchup{2%tbsp} on the toasted burger buns. Place your
burger patty on top then slice the @vine tomatoes{4} really thinly widthways.
Lay the tomato and rocket on top and serve with your rustic chips on the side.